@node "intro" "Introduction"

@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

prism2.device is a SANA-II network driver for 11Mbps wireless Ethernet cards
based on the Prism II chipset and variants. It supports PCMCIA cards in the
A1200/A600 and PCI cards in all AmigaOS 4 systems and in PCs running
Amithlon.

This version of prism2.device supports WPA and WPA2 encryption, including
both TKIP and CCMP (AES) encryption modes. However, not all hardware
supports all encryption modes. Cards with Intersil firmware support WEP,
TKIP and CCMP, while cards with Lucent/Agere firmware only support WEP and
TKIP.

Intersil cards also need to be flashed with an upgraded firmware to support
WPA/WPA2 encryption. Lucent/Agere cards do not need a firmware upgrade and
have the additional advantage of performing TKIP encryption in hardware.
However, Lucent/Agere cards do not work with some modern access points
(routers). Such access points even cause later Lucent/Agere cards to lock up
as soon as the card detects them. Note in particular that this means that a
neighbour's access point could trigger this behaviour, even if no attempt is
made to connect to it.

The table below shows compatibility information for prism2.device with a
variety of wireless cards. For cards not listed below, you will have to do
some research. If a card's chipset is stated as Orinoco, Agere, Prism II or
Prism 2.5 @{u}and@{uu} its bus type is PCMCIA or PCI, it is likely to work.
Some Prism 3 cards may also work if they have a flash memory. Note that a
few otherwise-compatible PCMCIA cards are 3.3V-only and therefore
incompatible with the A1200/A600. If the card doesn't match these
requirements, it will definitely @{u}not@{uu} work.

All compatible PCI cards use Intersil firmware and therefore support WEP,
TKIP and CCMP. Lucent/Agere PCMCIA cards can usually be identified by their
white pin connectors.

