@node "install" "Installation and Usage"

@{u}@{b}Hardware requirements@{ub}@{uu}

One of the following systems is required:
 - An A600 or A1200.
 - An AmigaOS 4 system.
 - A PC running Amithlon.

@{u}@{b}Software requirements@{ub}@{uu}

prism2.device needs AmigaOS 3.0 or greater.

@{u}@{b}Firmware upgrade@{ub}@{uu}

Intersil cards need to have their firmware upgraded before they can use
WPA/WPA2. This procedure cannot be done in AmigaOS, and it is recommended
that it be done in a Windows PC.

Instructions on reflashing the firmware, and the required firmware files,
can be found at http://linux.junsun.net/intersil-prism/

It is advised that cards be reflashed with primary firmware 1.1.1 and
secondary firmware 1.7.4, as prism2.device has been tested with these
versions.

@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

To install prism2.device, run the 'Install' script. In your networking
software, set the SANA-II device name to @{b}networks/prism2.device@{ub}
and the unit number to @{b}0@{ub}.

This package includes a utility called WirelessManager that runs in the
background and sets up connections to wireless networks. Under AmigaOS 3,
the install script will add an entry to the S:User-Startup script to start
WirelessManager at boot.

Under AmigaOS 4, however, it is necessary to start WirelessManager from the
S:Startup-Sequence script instead to ensure that a wireless connection is
established before the TCP/IP stack starts its DHCP client. Since this
cannot be easily done by the install script, the following line should be
manually inserted just before AddNetInterface or Network-Startup is called:

    Run <>NIL: C:WirelessManager prism2.device

@{u}@{b}Wireless parameters@{ub}@{uu}

Parameters for your wireless networks are specified in the file
'ENVARC:Sys/Wireless.prefs'. You can choose to have this file created
automatically while running the 'Install' script. The installer lets you
create a configuration for a single WPA/WPA2-encrypted network. If you need
other options, or want to configure more than one network, you will need to
edit 'ENVARC:Sys/Wireless.prefs' in a text editor. Below are some examples
of network configurations that can be used.

# A WPA/WPA2-encrypted network with a textual passphrase
# (using a textual WPA/WPA2 passphrase will cause a start-up delay of up to
# several minutes on a slow CPU)

network={
	ssid="mynet1"
	psk="yOuRsEcRetwpAKeY"
}

# A WPA/WPA2-encrypted network with a hexadecimal key
# (note that the key will need to be recalculated if the SSID is changed)

network={
	ssid="mynet1"
	psk=b368b34a7ba4051bea1f9aed30a179d4e56ae1c8624c1fabd2f5f0f7c0db12a3
}

# A WEP-encrypted network with a hexadecimal key

network={
	ssid="mynet2"
	key_mgmt=NONE
	wep_key0=123456789abcdef123456789ab
	wep_tx_keyidx=0
}

# A WEP-encrypted network with a textual password

network={
	ssid="mynet3"
	key_mgmt=NONE
	wep_key0="yourpassword1"
	wep_tx_keyidx=0
}

# Match any unencrypted network

network={
	key_mgmt=NONE
}


@{u}@{b}A1200 hardware bug@{ub}@{uu}

The A1200 (but not the A600) has a hardware bug which prevents a PCMCIA card
being reset except on insertion or removal. There are both hardware and
software remedies for this problem. The software solution is CardReset
(util/boot/CardReset.lha on Aminet). There are several different types of
hardware fixes, both DIY and commercial.

@{u}@{b}Problems@{ub}@{uu}

Miami will cause the system to hang if a PCMCIA card is removed while
online. Re-insertion won't help.

